<article id="post-204497" class="post-204497 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-analysis-frontpage">
<div class="entry-content">
		<div data-trackable="article-body" data-legal-copy="">
<p>In the north, Islamic fighters are defying a military offensive by five countries, while in the south, militants have crippled the economy by blowing up oil pipelines. Crises abound in Nigeria, despite promises by President Muhammadu Buhari to make Africa’s most populous country safer.</p>
<p>More than a year-and-a-half after he was inaugurated, analysts acknowledge that progress has been made against the Islamist Boko Haram group in the country’s north-east, the country’s main security challenge.</p>
<p>Yet a lack of effective reforms in the military, as well as regular overbearing use of force by soldiers and police, has analysts worried that Mr Buhari’s attempts to make the country safer could backfire.</p>
<p>“Compared to two years ago when Boko Haram controlled a swath of land the size of Belgium, Nigeria is more stable,” says Michael Clyne, a political risk analyst specialising in Africa. “The problem is there’s now a greater range of threat actors that have their own military or militant capability.”</p>
<p>Those threats include clashes between nomadic cattle herdsmen and farmers. These are often the result of intercommunal grievances but have nevertheless raised tensions between the different ethnic groups and religions that make up Nigeria.</p>
<p>In the north, Islamic Movement in Nigeria, a Shia group, is protesting against the detention of its leader, who was captured after a battle with the army last year that killed more than 300 sect members. Those protests turned violent in October, leading to the deaths of 10 people and raising fears that supporters could take up arms again.</p>
<p>But none of these crises has had as much impact on Nigeria as Boko Haram, whose campaign to establish strict Islamic law in Nigeria’s north has left more than 20,000 people dead and forced more than 2m people from their homes since 2009, according to the United Nations.</p>
<p>At the height of their power in 2015, the insurgents took over parts of Nigeria’s north-eastern states and routinely sent suicide bombers into northern cities. Nigeria’s military has since pushed them out of much of that land, but the group has spread into neighbouring countries of Chad, Cameroon and Niger, and a faction of fighters has pledged allegiance to the Islamic State group waging war in Syria and Iraq.</p>
<p>Nigerian officials under Mr Buhari have repeatedly described Boko Haram as defeated, but Nnamdi Obasi, senior adviser on Nigeria for International Crisis Group, says the group is anything but. “Contrary to the government’s profession of clearing the remnants of Boko Haram, there is still some substantial resistance,” Mr Obasi says. Over one weekend in late October, the insurgents killed five soldiers in an ambush and sent suicide bombers into a big north-eastern city, killing nine.</p>
<p>Nigeria’s military is poorly equipped and ill-suited for the type of counterinsurgency strategy required to beat Boko Haram, says Cobus Claassens, managing director of Pilgrims Africa, a security company based in Lagos.</p>
<p>“The problem lies in their state of readiness, which is in a sorry, sorry state,” Mr Claassens says. “They may have the men, but then you can’t send men there wearing flip flops and rusty AK-47s or FN [rifles] with no ammunition. That’s not going to work.”</p>
<p>Yan St-Pierre of security consultancy Mosecon says the task of pacifying the north-east is not simply about exerting military power, but also demands the rebuilding of devastated areas and restoring trust in the police and soldiers.</p>
<p>Crises elsewhere in the country will require a similarly nuanced approach, analysts say. This year a militant group called the Niger Delta Avengers emerged in the country’s oil-producing heartland in the south.</p>
<p>Its strikes on pipelines cut Nigeria’s oil production levels from 2m to about 1.4m barrels a day at one point, sending the oil-dependent economy into a recession. It also sparked the emergence of more than a dozen other groups, each with their own demands.</p>
<p>The agendas of these groups are rooted in the poverty of the Niger Delta, which, despite being the economic engine of the country, is under-developed and polluted by oil spills.</p>
<p>The government has tried a two-pronged approach of sending the army after the militants but also offering to talk. Yet the attacks on pipelines continue. David Zounmenou, senior research fellow at South Africa-based Institute for Security Studies, says the region can only be pacified when people feel they benefit from the oil trade.</p>
<p>That will require investments in roads and power in the Niger Delta — a tough demand on a country where dilapidated infrastructure is widespread and two-thirds of people live in poverty.</p>
<h2 class="subhead subhead--standard">Stretched thin: Nigeria’s military is embroiled in several internal conflicts</h2>
<figure class="n-content-image n-content-image--center p402_hide">
<div class="n-image-wrapper n-image-wrapper--placeholder"><img class="n-image" sizes="(min-width: 46.25em) 600px, calc(100vw - 20px)" srcset="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7d7593b0-b274-11e6-a37c-f4a01f1b0fa1?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=600 600w, https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7d7593b0-b274-11e6-a37c-f4a01f1b0fa1?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=315 315w" alt="" /></div>
</figure>
<p><strong>1. Islamic Movement in Nigeria</strong></p>
<figure class="n-content-image n-content-image--full p402_hide">
<div class="n-image-wrapper n-image-wrapper--placeholder"><img class="n-image" sizes="(min-width: 76.25em) 700px, (min-width: 61.25em) 620px, (min-width: 46.25em) 700px, calc(100vw - 20px)" srcset="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F72baa690-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=700 700w, https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F72baa690-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=500 500w, https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F72baa690-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=300 300w" alt="" /></div>
<figcaption class="n-content-image__caption">Protesters from the Islamic Movement in Nigeria march in Kano © AFP</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>A minority Shia Muslim sect, the Islamic Movement in Nigeria has long had a tense relationship with its neighbours in the northern Kaduna state. Last December its headquarters were demolished after a clash with the army and its leader, Ibrahim Zakzaky, was taken into custody. The army claimed it was defending itself following an attack on a top general. The fighting killed more than 300 people. Since then, the IMN has staged periodic protests demanding Mr Zakzaky’s release. The Kaduna state government banned IMN in October. Around 20 people have since been killed in two separate clashes between IMN members and police.</p>
<p><strong>2. Farmers and herdsmen</strong></p>
<figure class="n-content-image n-content-image--full p402_hide">
<div class="n-image-wrapper n-image-wrapper--placeholder"><img class="n-image" sizes="(min-width: 76.25em) 700px, (min-width: 61.25em) 620px, (min-width: 46.25em) 700px, calc(100vw - 20px)" srcset="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d0ecde8-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=700 700w, https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d0ecde8-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=500 500w, https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6d0ecde8-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=300 300w" alt="" /></div>
<figcaption class="n-content-image__caption">A Fulani herdsman © Getty</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Nigerians have been farming for centuries. Nomadic cattle herders from the arid north have been migrating south for land to graze on for a similar period of time. The groups often coexist without conflict. But a series of clashes between the two groups this year has raised tensions in the countryside. Farmers, who are often Christians, complain cattle trample their crops and herdsmen attack them in their field. Herdsmen, many of whom are Muslim, say farmers attack them. Reasons for the clashes vary, but they have left dozens dead in the country’s southern half. “If it were ever to lead to the type of tit-for-tat Muslim-Christian killings you see in other parts of Africa — Central African Republic, for example — that would be another spiralling crisis,” says Michael Clyne, a political risk analyst. “There’s precedence for that in the region and little precedence for solutions.”</p>
<p><strong>3. Niger Delta</strong></p>
<p>At the beginning of the year, the Niger Delta Avengers burst on to the scene with a series of pipeline bombings that cut Nigeria’s oil production so drastically that the campaign has been cited as one of the main reasons for tipping Nigeria, then Africa’s largest economy, into a recession. The insurgents have since been joined by more than a dozen other groups, some of whom have claimed attacks, while others have merely threatened violence. The military has launched offensives into the creeks of the delta while government ministers have offered negotiations. The attacks have not stopped. Nnamdi Obasi, senior Nigeria adviser for the International Crisis Group, says talks are the best way to resolve the crisis.</p>
<p><strong>4. Biafra separatists</strong></p>
<figure class="n-content-image n-content-image--full p402_hide">
<div class="n-image-wrapper n-image-wrapper--placeholder"><img class="n-image" sizes="(min-width: 76.25em) 700px, (min-width: 61.25em) 620px, (min-width: 46.25em) 700px, calc(100vw - 20px)" srcset="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7c4462fa-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=700 700w, https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7c4462fa-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=500 500w, https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.prod-us.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7c4462fa-b2ba-11e6-9c37-5787335499a0?source=next&amp;fit=scale-down&amp;width=300 300w" alt="" /></div>
<figcaption class="n-content-image__caption">Demonstrators during a protest calling for the release of pro-Biafra leader Nnamdi Kanu © AFP</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Agitations for a return of the Republic of Biafra — a section of Nigeria’s south-east that broke away in 1967 and was reabsorbed three years later after a ruinous civil war — have been simmering for years. They boiled over after President Muhammadu Buhari took office last year, with a series of protests in south-eastern cities.</p>
<p>Separatist groups complain they are not treated fairly by the federal government. The arrest of Nnamdi Kanu, an activist who operated a radio station that acted as a mouthpiece of Biafra agitators, intensified the rallies. The discontent appeared to reach a peak in May when clashes between protesters and the military in the city of Onitsha led to at least 40 deaths, according to Amnesty International. The human rights group said soldiers opened fire on unarmed civilians.</p>
<p><strong>5. Boko Haram</strong></p>
<p>The seven years of Islamic insurgency in north-east Nigeria constitutes the most destructive crisis Nigeria has faced since its three-year civil war ended in 1970. Around 20,000 people have died. More than 2m people have fled the conflict, ending up in camps or communities in Nigeria or in neighbouring Cameroon, Chad and Niger. While parts of Nigeria’s north-east have become safer, the years of combat have wrecked food supplies. The United Nations says 4.5m need food assistance in the region, and 75,000 children could die if they do not get help. Aid agencies believe famine may already be occurring in parts of the region too dangerous to access.</p>
